item.description:
arXiv:2504.04286v1 Announce Type: new 
Abstract: This article presents and compares four approaches for computing the rotation of a point about an axis by an angle in $\mathbb{R}^3$. We illustrate these methods by computing, by hand, the rotation of point $P=(1,0,1)^T$ about axis $\mathbf{a}=(1,1,1)^T$ by angle $\theta=60^\circ$ (following the right-hand rule). The four methods considered are:
  (1) an ad hoc geometric method exploiting a symmetry in the situation;
  (2) a projection method that sets up a new coordinate system using the dot and cross products;
  (3) a matrix method which rotates the standard basis and uses matrix-vector multiplication;
  (4) a Geometric (Clifford) Algebra method that represents the rotation as a double reflection via a rotor.
  All methods yield the same exact result: $P'=\left(\tfrac{4}{3},\tfrac{1}{3},\tfrac{1}{3}\right)^T$.
